# Solving the Set Equinumerability Problem in Lean 4

To solve this problem, we need to prove that if a function `f` is one-to-one on a set `A` and `image f A = B`, then `A \ {a}` is equinumerable to `B \ {b}` where `a ∈ A` and `f a = b`.

First, let's think about how to construct the bijection between `A \ {a}` and `B \ {b}`. We have a function `f` from `U` to `V`, and we're considering the restriction of `f` to the set `A \ {a}`. The image of this restricted function will be a subset of `B \ {b}`.

Since `f` is one-to-one on `A`, the restriction of `f` to `A \ {a}` is also one-to-one. Let's denote this restricted function as `f'`. Then `f'` is a bijection from `A \ {a}` to its image in `B \ {b}`. So we need to show that the image of `f'` is exactly `B \ {b}`.

We know that `image f A = B`. So every element in `B` is the image of some element in `A` under `f`. If `y ∈ B \ {b}`, then `y ∈ B` and `y ≠ b`. So `y` is the image of some `x ∈ A` under `f`, and `x ≠ a` (since `f a = b` and `y ≠ b`). Therefore, `y` is in the image of `A \ {a}` under `f`.

Conversely, if `y` is in the image of `A \ {a}` under `f`, then `y = f x` for some `x ∈ A \ {a}`. Then `x ≠ a`, so `f x ≠ f a = b`, so `y ≠ b`. Thus `y ∈ B \ {b}`.

So we have a bijection `f'` from `A \ {a}` to `B \ {b}`. This will give us the required equinumerability.

